    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/rh-index-comparison-5op",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Relative Hemolysis Index Comparison — 5 Operating Points (PRIMARY)",
      "description": "CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RH) was compared against in-vitro experimental measurements at five flow-speed operating points (Q = 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 L/min at 3000 RPM) for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry. Experimental hemolysis measurements were obtained using the modified index of hemolysis (MIH) protocol with bovine blood at 37°C, hematocrit 33±2%, and plasma-free hemoglobin quantified by Drabkin's reagent spectrophotometry. The CFD solver employed a power-law hemolysis damage accumulation model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger correlation) integrated along Lagrangian particle trajectories seeded uniformly at the inlet. Mesh independence was confirmed at 4.2 million polyhedral cells (GCI < 2.1% across all operating points). Turbulence was modeled via SST k-ω with low-Reynolds-number correction active in near-wall regions (y+ < 1). Predicted RH values ranged from 0.61 to 0.89 across the five operating points, all satisfying the RH < 1 acceptance criterion. Mean absolute percentage error between CFD and experiment was 8.3%, within the pre-specified 15% tolerance band. This result constitutes the primary quantitative validation evidence supporting the credibility claim. The simulation campaign was conducted over a three-week period by two senior CFD analysts using ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 on a 128-core HPC cluster, with post-processing performed in EnSight 2022.2. All intermediate result files, convergence histories, and particle tracking datasets are archived in the project data management system under accession number FDA-GCP-CFD-2023-047.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/fda-generic-pump-experimental-hemolysis"
    },
